# Prisma Design System Component Rules

## Core Principles

This project is built exclusively with the **Prisma Design System**. All UI components, styling, and patterns must come from the Prisma design system packages.

## Component Usage

### Always Use Prisma Components

1. **Never create custom UI components** when a Prisma component exists
2. **Always import from Prisma packages** for:
   - Buttons
   - Forms (inputs, selects, checkboxes, radio buttons, etc.)
   - Navigation (headers, footers, menus, tabs, breadcrumbs)
   - Layout components (grid, containers, spacing)
   - Typography (headings, paragraphs, text)
   - Cards and containers
   - Modals and dialogs
   - Tooltips and popovers
   - Tables and data display
   - Loading states and spinners
   - Icons
   - Alerts and notifications
   - Badges and tags
   - Any other UI elements

3. **Check Prisma documentation first** before building any component
4. **Custom components are only allowed** for:
   - Business logic specific to this prototype
   - Complex compositions of Prisma components
   - Components that genuinely don't exist in the design system

### Component Discovery

Before creating any component:
1. Search the Prisma design system documentation
2. Check available Prisma npm packages
3. Review Prisma component examples
4. Ask the user if unsure whether a component exists in Prisma

## Styling Rules

### Use Prisma Design Tokens

1. **Never use hardcoded values** for:
   - Colors (use Prisma color tokens)
   - Spacing (use Prisma spacing scale)
   - Typography (use Prisma font sizes, weights, line heights)
   - Border radius (use Prisma radius tokens)
   - Shadows (use Prisma shadow tokens)
   - Breakpoints (use Prisma responsive breakpoints)

2. **Import design tokens** from Prisma packages:
   ```tsx
   import { colors, spacing, typography } from '@prisma/design-tokens';
   ```

3. **Use Prisma's theming system** if available
4. **Follow Prisma's CSS-in-JS or CSS module patterns** as defined in their documentation

### CSS Guidelines

1. **Prefer Prisma utility classes** over custom CSS
2. **Use Prisma's layout system** (Grid, Flex, Stack, etc.)
3. **Custom CSS only for**:
   - Prototype-specific layouts
   - Animations not provided by Prisma
   - Edge cases not covered by the design system

## Code Standards

### Imports

Always import Prisma components from the correct package:


// ✅ Correct
import { Button, Input, Card } from '@prisma/components';
import { colors, spacing } from '@prisma/design-tokens';

// ❌ Incorrect - don't create custom versions
import { Button } from '@/components/Button';
```

### TypeScript

1. Use Prisma's TypeScript types for component props
2. Extend Prisma types when needed, don't recreate them
3. Import types from Prisma packages:
   ```tsx
   import type { ButtonProps, InputProps } from '@prisma/components';
   ```

### Composition

When building complex features:

```tsx
// ✅ Correct - compose Prisma components
import { Card, Button, Stack, Text } from '@prisma/components';

export function UserCard({ user }) {
  return (
    <Card>
      <Stack spacing="md">
        <Text variant="h3">{user.name}</Text>
        <Text variant="body">{user.email}</Text>
        <Button variant="primary">Edit</Button>
      </Stack>
    </Card>
  );
}

// ❌ Incorrect - creating custom styled div
export function UserCard({ user }) {
  return (
    <div className="custom-card">
      <h3>{user.name}</h3>
      <p>{user.email}</p>
      <button>Edit</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Package Installation

### Before Installing Any Package

1. **Check if Prisma provides it first**
   - UI libraries: Use Prisma components instead
   - Icon libraries: Use Prisma icons
   - CSS frameworks: Use Prisma styles

2. **Only install external packages for**:
   - Data fetching (React Query, SWR, etc.)
   - State management (if not provided by Prisma)
   - Utilities (lodash, date-fns, etc.)
   - Backend/API functionality

3. **Never install**:
   - Alternative component libraries (Material-UI, Ant Design, Chakra, etc.)
   - CSS frameworks (Tailwind, Bootstrap, etc.) unless Prisma is built on them
   - UI libraries that duplicate Prisma functionality

## File Structure

### Component Organization

```
components/
  FeatureName/
    FeatureName.tsx       # Compose Prisma components here
    styles.module.css     # Minimal custom styles only
    types.ts              # Business logic types
```

### Example Component

```tsx
// components/ProductCard/ProductCard.tsx
import { Card, Stack, Text, Button, Image } from '@prisma/components';
import { spacing, colors } from '@prisma/design-tokens';
import type { Product } from './types';

interface ProductCardProps {
  product: Product;
  onAddToCart: (id: string) => void;
}

export function ProductCard({ product, onAddToCart }: ProductCardProps) {
  return (
    <Card elevation="md">
      <Stack spacing={spacing.lg}>
        <Image 
          src={product.image} 
          alt={product.name}
          aspectRatio="16/9"
        />
        <Stack spacing={spacing.sm}>
          <Text variant="h4">{product.name}</Text>
          <Text variant="body" color={colors.textSecondary}>
            {product.description}
          </Text>
          <Text variant="h5" color={colors.primary}>
            ${product.price}
          </Text>
        </Stack>
        <Button 
          variant="primary" 
          onClick={() => onAddToCart(product.id)}
          fullWidth
        >
          Add to Cart
        </Button>
      </Stack>
    </Card>
  );
}
```

## Validation Checklist

Before submitting any work, verify:

- [ ] All UI elements use Prisma components
- [ ] No custom buttons, inputs, or basic UI components
- [ ] Design tokens used for all styling values
- [ ] Prisma's layout system used for positioning
- [ ] TypeScript types imported from Prisma packages
- [ ] No conflicting UI libraries installed
- [ ] Component names clearly describe business logic, not UI primitives
- [ ] Custom styles are minimal and only for prototype-specific needs

## When in Doubt

1. **Ask the user** which Prisma component to use
2. **Reference Prisma documentation** before building
3. **Prefer composition** over creation
4. **Think "assemble" not "build"** - we're assembling Prisma components, not building a design system

## Exceptions

Exceptions to these rules require explicit approval. Document any exceptions with:
- Reason for exception
- Why Prisma component couldn't be used
- Link to discussion/decision

---

**Remember**: This is a Prisma design system prototype. The goal is to showcase and use Prisma components, not to create custom UI. Every custom component is a missed opportunity to use the design system.
